    <p class="lead" style="font-size: 1.15rem; color: var(--gc-ink-muted);">
        A one-shot key agreement primitive built on hash preimage
        resistance and statistical drift &mdash; no DLP, no lattices.
    </p>

    <p>
        Classical <em>Diffie&ndash;Hellman</em> rests on the discrete
        logarithm problem; post-quantum ML&#8209;KEM on
        <em>module&#8209;LWE</em>. Grata Cascade adds an independent
        third option: agreement on a 32-byte key
        <span class="text-monospace">K*</span> via &asymp;&nbsp;49 rounds
        of public hashes and AES&#8209;CBC ciphertexts, whose security
        rests <em>solely</em> on the preimage resistance of the
        underlying hash function. The intended position in a hybrid
        post-quantum composition is the third independent layer &mdash;
        <span class="text-monospace">X25519&nbsp;&oplus;&nbsp;ML&#8209;KEM&#8209;768&nbsp;&oplus;&nbsp;Grata&nbsp;Cascade</span>.
    </p>

    <h2>What this demo shows</h2>

    <p>
        Open two (or more) browser tabs. Each one is auto-assigned a
        unique handle in the form <code>color&#8209;animal</code>
        (e.g. <code>blue&#8209;bear</code>) and sees other connected
        users in the lobby. Pick a peer, send them a pair request;
        once they <em>Accept</em>, both tabs start computing
        independently &mdash; one in role&nbsp;A, the other in role&nbsp;B.
    </p>

    <p>
        The server acts <em>strictly as a relay</em>. It does not see
        the keys nor the protocol state &mdash; only forwards public
        messages from A to B and back, exactly what a passive
        eavesdropper would see in §&nbsp;1.5 of the paper. Once the
        protocol terminates, both sides independently derive the same
        <span class="text-monospace">K*</span>, and the UI displays a
        short <em>Safety Number</em> in the form
        <span class="text-monospace">XXXX&#8209;XXXX</span> &mdash; an
        out-of-band check that both sides did agree on the same key.
    </p>

    <div class="gc-disclaimer" role="note">
        <div class="gc-disclaimer-title">Demo only &mdash; passive&#8209;adversary scenario</div>
        The server is an honest relay, not an authenticated transport.
        Active MITM is <em>not</em> blocked here &mdash; real-world
        deployment requires TLS / Noise plus out-of-band key
        verification. See the demo's disclaimer section and §&nbsp;1.5
        of the paper for details.
    </div>

